<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
I find that a lot of them are people who use &quot;free&quot; hosting (Geocities, etc) and those things absolutely suck when it comes to bandwidth allowance.  All it takes is a few hits and your site is shut down until the top of the hour.  That can get frustrating, as people stop visiting your site.
<br />

<br />
It's really not that expensive to buy hosting these days.  The company I work through sells a base plan to the general public for $5 a month.  (I buy in bulk because I design websites for people so it's even cheaper).  Anyhow, you get something like 500 megs of storage and 20 gigs of bandwidth for that price... which is plenty for a site just starting out.  And there are a LOT of decent web hosts out there providing similar packages.  If a person is willing to spend one McDonald's lunch a month, they can have hosted sites that  don't go down every hour... AND they don't have all those pop-ups and adverts that the freebie hosts use.  Plus, you spend a little less than $10 a year and you get to register your own cool website name.  Like welovebeth.com or beth-is-awesome.com.   <img src="images/smiles/icon_cool.gif" alt="Cool" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
I'm in the process of moving my photo galleries right now and am going to be building a new site for my family genealogy.  I'm starting with a gig of disk space... but as Beth will tell you if you ever ask her about the stats for this site, pictures eat a lot of disk space... so I'll probably be adding more soon.
<br />

<br />
In my opinion, the free-hosted type sites are the ones I tend to see disappear more frequently than others.</td>
</tr>
