Actually, I'll be running Gallery within this site.  It actually makes a lot more sense to have my cemetery photos linked with a genealogy site anyway, rather than my business site.  Once I've gotten everything built and transferred, I'll let you know and you can update the links from here.  Nothing, in theory, should change... just the domain address.
<br />

<br />
<table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr><td><span class="genmed"><strong>graveaddiction wrote:</strong></span></td></tr><tr><td class="quote">My big advice to someone looking for a host? Make sure you do a search on the company and read user reviews. The first host I picked was recommended by a coworker, but it was HORRIBLE. The site was down more than it was up, they made tons of billing mistakes, and their tech support NEVER responded (which was funny since they claimed to have 24/7 support). I was constantly frustrated. I did a search on their name, and I found countless bad reviews...in fact, I think I only found one good review online! I wish I would have done that before I chose them as my host. Needless to say, I cancelled my service with them as soon as the contract was up! My current host is a million times better.</td></tr></table>
<br />

<br />
I agree 150%.  I got lucky, I guess.  My host was recommended by a colleague who had nothing but good experience.  I was a little leary because the price seemed so cheap.  I moved one site I manage over just to test things out... my provider didn't require a contract.  Everything worked well so I proceeded to become a &quot;reseller&quot; (in name only, so I could get bulk space and then charge my clients for it).  Prior to this, one of the sites I managed was on Network Solutions and one was on Verio.  They were good for bandwidth, but their control panels were horrendous.  Sloooooooooow, to say the least.  Like I say, I got lucky, in that I had a low usage site I could test with... and the host didn't require contracts.
<br />

<br />
My tech contact uses AIM mobile on his cell phone, so I can pretty much get him anytime via AIM if I need him urgently.  (About once every 4 or 5 months on average)
<br />

<br />
One other suggestion for your own sites... use someplace like GoDaddy to register your domains.  Two of the sites I manage were originally registered through Verio and my client was paying $25 a year for each domain name.  Needless to say, I moved his registrations to GoDaddy when he became a client... and it only costs $9 a year per domain.  (Less if you buy multiple years)
<br />

<br />
Anyway... just some thoughts if someone is thinking about plunging in to having a website.</td>
</tr>
