<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
I've made some of the same mistakes you both mentioned in your posts with my past websites. Maybe website issues are what causes a lot of ghost hunting groups to disappear from the web. 
<br />

<br />
I had an eCommerce site hosted by Network Solutions back in the late 90's and the control panels are a big pain in the ass. My site was built with ASP, SQL Server, and Flash before they were popular and well known, so nine times out of ten we knew more than the tech support person we were working on problems. They did stick with us throughout the somewhat grueling process of figuring problems we encountered and were always easy to contact. Aside from the un-user-friendly control interfaces my only complaint about Network Solutions is that they were quite expensive. 
<br />

<br />
I've also used jumpline.com and they were great but also quite expensive. 
<br />

<br />
I have a friend from Coshocton, who annoys the crap out of me, who also runs an IT Consulting firm so I'm thinking about using him to host my 2 new websites that will be going up in the next few weeks. It seems like he has a good quality service and it's moderately priced so I'm thinking about giving him a shot. This is the same guy who works at Nationwide doing database admin work. I sometimes wonder if he really knows what he's talking about but I think I'm going to give him a shot. 
<br />

<br />
It is important to check out hosting companies before you sign up with them. There are a lot of third party re-sellers who are so far down the line from the actual company that owns the hosting equipment tech support is terrible. I like moderately priced companies...not too cheap...not ridiculously expensive.</td>
</tr>
