<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
Oh... another lesson I learned.  The cheaper web hosts often do &quot;name-based&quot; websites.  In a nutshell, they have one IP address  which gets the request and then looks up your domain name on their server.  Honestly, for simple sites such as &quot;Bob's Family Website&quot;, this is just fine.  However, if you intend to do things such as eCommerce and will need to use SSL secure certificates to take personal information, you've got to have an &quot;IP-based&quot; website with it's own unique IP identifier.  My host, like many others, offers both.  I set up a couple of online stores for clients and had to build them on IP based sites.
<br />

<br />
Just another tidbit in &quot;Webhosting 101&quot;   <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="Razz" border="0" /></td>
</tr>
